static char __pyx_doc_22FiniteDifferenceEngine_22FiniteDifferenceEngine___init__[] = "\n        @coefficients@ is a dict of tuple, function pairs with c[i,j] referring to the\n        coefficient of the i j derivative, dU/didj. Absent pairs are counted as zeros.\n\n        The functions MUST be able to handle dims+1 arguments, with the first\n        being time and the rest corresponding to the dimensions given by @grid.shape@.\n\n        Still need a good way to handle cross terms.\n\n        N.B. You don't actually want to do this with lambdas. They aren't real\n        closures. Weird things might happen.\n\n        Ex. (2D grid)\n\n            {(None,): lambda t, x0, x1: 0.06 # 0th derivative\n              (0,)  : lambda t, x0, x1: 0.5,\n              (0,0) : lambda t, x0, x1: x,\n              # python magic lets be more general than (2*x1*t)\n              (1,)  : lambda t, *dims: 2*dims[1]*t\n              (0,1) : lambda t, *dims: dims[0]*dims[1]}\n\n        is interpreted as:\n            0.5*(dU/dx1) + x1*(d\302\262U/dx1\302\262) + 2*x2*t*(dU/dx2)\n                + 0*(d\302\262U/dx2\302\262) + x1*x2*(d\302\262U/dx1dx2)\n\n        A similar scheme applies for the boundaries conditions.  @boundaries@\n        is a dict of 2-tuples corresponding to the lower and upper boundary\n        (where lower means low index in @grid.mesh@). Each can have one of\n        two possible values.\n\n        The first element is a number corresponding to the type of boundary\n        condition.\n            None signifies free boundaries, simply satisfying the PDE.\n            0 is a dirchlet boundary condition\n            1 is a Von Neuman boundary\n\n        It's up to you to make sure this makes sense. If you specify a\n        dirichlet boundary somewhere, then it doesn't make sense to also\n        specify a Von Neumann boundary there.\n\n        The second element is a function in the same form as for the coefficients,\n        representing the value of the boundary.\n\n        Ex. (Heston PDE, x0 = spot, x1 = variance)\n\n                    # 0'th d""erivative term (ex. -rU)\n                    # This can only depend on time!\n            {()    : lambda t: -self.r\n                    # dirichlet: U = 0         # VN: dUdS = 1\n             (0,)  : ((1, lambda *args: 0), (1, lambda *args:1))\n                    # dirichlet: U = 0         # Free boundary\n             (0,0) : ((1, lambda *args: 0), (None, lambda *x: None)),\n                    # Free boundary at low variance\n             (1,)  : ((None, lambda *x: None),\n                    # dirichlet: intrinsic value at high variance\n                       (1, lambda t, *dims: np.maximum(0, dim[0]-k)))\n                    # Free boundary at low variance\n                    # VN: second derivative is 0 at high variance\n            (1,1)  : ((None, lambda *x: None), (1, lambda *args:0))}\n\n\n        Again we do a similar encoding for the FD schemes used.\n\n        @schemes@ is a dict of tuples of dicts as follows.\n\n        Ex.  33:         """


 34:         @coefficients@ is a dict of tuple, function pairs with c[i,j] referring to the


 35:         coefficient of the i j derivative, dU/didj. Absent pairs are counted as zeros.


 36: 


 37:         The functions MUST be able to handle dims+1 arguments, with the first


 38:         being time and the rest corresponding to the dimensions given by @grid.shape@.


 39: 


 40:         Still need a good way to handle cross terms.


 41: 


 42:         N.B. You don't actually want to do this with lambdas. They aren't real


 43:         closures. Weird things might happen.


 44: 


 45:         Ex. (2D grid)


 46: 


 47:             {(None,): lambda t, x0, x1: 0.06 # 0th derivative


 48:               (0,)  : lambda t, x0, x1: 0.5,


 49:               (0,0) : lambda t, x0, x1: x,


 50:               # python magic lets be more general than (2*x1*t)


 51:               (1,)  : lambda t, *dims: 2*dims[1]*t


 52:               (0,1) : lambda t, *dims: dims[0]*dims[1]}


 53: 


 54:         is interpreted as:


 55:             0.5*(dU/dx1) + x1*(dU/dx1) + 2*x2*t*(dU/dx2)


 56:                 + 0*(dU/dx2) + x1*x2*(dU/dx1dx2)


 57: 


 58:         A similar scheme applies for the boundaries conditions.  @boundaries@


 59:         is a dict of 2-tuples corresponding to the lower and upper boundary


 60:         (where lower means low index in @grid.mesh@). Each can have one of


 61:         two possible values.


 62: 


 63:         The first element is a number corresponding to the type of boundary


 64:         condition.


 65:             None signifies free boundaries, simply satisfying the PDE.


 66:             0 is a dirchlet boundary condition


 67:             1 is a Von Neuman boundary


 68: 


 69:         It's up to you to make sure this makes sense. If you specify a


 70:         dirichlet boundary somewhere, then it doesn't make sense to also


 71:         specify a Von Neumann boundary there.


 72: 


 73:         The second element is a function in the same form as for the coefficients,


 74:         representing the value of the boundary.


 75: 


 76:         Ex. (Heston PDE, x0 = spot, x1 = variance)


 77: 


 78:                     # 0'th derivative term (ex. -rU)


 79:                     # This can only depend on time!


 80:             {()    : lambda t: -self.r


 81:                     # dirichlet: U = 0         # VN: dUdS = 1


 82:              (0,)  : ((1, lambda *args: 0), (1, lambda *args:1))


 83:                     # dirichlet: U = 0         # Free boundary


 84:              (0,0) : ((1, lambda *args: 0), (None, lambda *x: None)),


 85:                     # Free boundary at low variance


 86:              (1,)  : ((None, lambda *x: None),


 87:                     # dirichlet: intrinsic value at high variance


 88:                        (1, lambda t, *dims: np.maximum(0, dim[0]-k)))


 89:                     # Free boundary at low variance


 90:                     # VN: second derivative is 0 at high variance


 91:             (1,1)  : ((None, lambda *x: None), (1, lambda *args:0))}


 92: 


 93: 


 94:         Again we do a similar encoding for the FD schemes used.


 95: 


 96:         @schemes@ is a dict of tuples of dicts as follows.


 97: 


 98:         Ex. (Centered in all cases. Switch to upwinding at index 10 in


 99:                 convection term in x1 dimension.)


 100: 


 101:             {(0,) : ({"scheme": "center"},),


 102:             (0,0): ({"scheme": "center"},),


 103:             (1,) : ({"scheme": "center"},


 104:                     {"scheme": "backward", "from" : flip_idx_var}),


 105:             (1,1): ({"scheme": "center"},)}


 106: 


 107:         Any missing values are determined by @self.default_scheme@ and


 108:         @self.default_order@ (making this particular example largely


 109:         redundant).


 110: 


 111:         Can't do this with C/Cuda of course... maybe cython?


 112:         """
